## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three distinct bugs** in this component. They compound each other, causing rapid listener accumulation with each scroll or resize event.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Effect Runs on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
});
```

Without a dependency array `[]`, React re-executes this effect after **every single render**. The problem is that the state updates inside the scroll handler (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`) each trigger a re-render, which re-runs the effect, which registers **more listeners**, which fire and trigger **more re-renders**. It's a self-feeding loop:

```
scroll event
  → setState (3×)
    → re-render
      → useEffect runs again
        → 2 NEW listeners added (old ones never removed)
          → next scroll event fires ALL accumulated listeners
            → even more setState calls → even more re-renders → ...
```

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Are Never Removed)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

`useEffect` supports returning a **cleanup function** that React calls:
- Before re-running the effect (when deps change), and
- When the component **unmounts**

Without it, every listener registered during the component's lifetime stays permanently attached to the `window` object — even after the user navigates away. Navigate away and back 10 times? You've potentially got **hundreds or thousands of orphaned listeners** all firing on every scroll event, each one calling `setState` on an unmounted component (React 16) or accumulating silently (React 17+), consuming CPU and memory indefinitely.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Can't Be Removed

```jsx
// ❌ New function reference created each time — impossible to removeEventListener
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
```

`removeEventListener` requires the **exact same function reference** that was passed to `addEventListener`. An inline arrow function creates a brand-new object each time it's evaluated. Even if you tried to add cleanup, this would silently fail:

```js
// This does NOTHING — different function instance
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // ❌ new reference, no match
```

You must save the handler to a named variable so both calls reference the same function.

---

## Bonus Bug — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

Because `lastScrollY` is a state variable captured by the closure, any accumulated "old" listener instances close over a **stale** value of `lastScrollY`. The direction detection (`currentScrollY > lastScrollY`) would be comparing against an outdated snapshot from a previous render cycle. Moving it to a `useRef` eliminates both the stale closure problem and the need to include it in the dependency array.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Immediately Visible

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **double-invokes effects on purpose**: it mounts → runs cleanup → remounts the component. This is designed to expose exactly this class of bug. Without cleanup, you'd see 2× (or 4× with the missing dep array) event listeners registered before a single scroll event fires. In production, Strict Mode's double-invoke doesn't happen, so the bug is less obvious at first but grows progressively worse with user interaction.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // useRef instead of useState for lastScrollY:
    //   - It's not displayed in the UI (no render needed)
    //   - Mutating a ref doesn't trigger a re-render
    //   - Avoids stale closure without needing it in the dep array
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named references — required so removeEventListener can match them
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY; // Mutate ref directly — no re-render
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        // Register listeners
        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup function — React calls this:
        //   1. Before the effect re-runs (if deps change)
        //   2. When the component unmounts
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // ✅ Empty array — run once on mount, clean up on unmount

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Effect runs every render | No dependency array | Add `[]` — run once on mount |
| Listeners never removed on unmount | No cleanup function | Return `() => removeEventListener(...)` |
| Old listeners can't be removed | Anonymous arrow functions | Assign handlers to named `const` variables |
| Stale `lastScrollY` in closure | State variable captured at render time | Replace `useState` with `useRef` |

The corrected component registers exactly **2 listeners** on mount and removes both cleanly on unmount, regardless of how many times the user navigates to and from the page.

